segments.text: This is Debra Beale.
I am interviewing Mr. Fred J. Benson on the history of Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
The date is June 5th, 1984.
And the other interview you gave us in the background, we don't really need to go into that all again, unless you want to.
but I'd like to know what your first assessment was of this place.
Well, when I first came here as a graduate student back in 1935 or 1936, the permit station was the responsibility of
Mr. Giske was the college architect.
Mr. Giske was very much interested in ventilation and heating and that sort of thing.
They were doing a lot of research work back then.
primarily on TV and that sort of thing.
So you got involved as a grad student?
No, I wasn't particularly involved in it.
I knew about it, but I was quite friendly with seven guys who were working on it.
And we basically left the university.
T.R.
Scramps
came in, and he had due respect to the experiment station, and he was also responsible for the University's building program.
And Mr. Gilchrist was the Dean of Engineering at the time, and he was very much interested in

freight rates, in fact felt that the state of Texas was being discriminated against, and we established new freight rates, so we had a rather substantial project to carry on, so freight rates to and from the Texas courts
destination and origin in comparison with similar commodities and similar lengths of trips in other parts of the country.
We also had another fairly large project in the study of bridges, which was carried on by
Now the freight rate study, when did that finally wind down?
Because that went on for years.
Yes, it did.
I would guess it probably ended sometime in the early 50s.
And out of that group,
Originated in the group of Belvedere, Illinois, as well as Texas.
That's the same group.
And that still exists.
So the industrial survey is what grew out of the freight rail study?
Presumably.
If you really want to pursue that phase of it, you've got to go talk to Jim Bradford.
Go to Jim Bradford.
Potential terms.
And I think we started back in the late 40's around Jim Randall.
Were you involved in TEAS as a professor before?
I really wasn't involved in TEAS directly until after World War II when we began to do
I've done a fair amount of research work in civil engineering in the Highway Pavement field.
I've done work with a lot of .
In the Highway Pavement, TTI was established in 55.
Was that something that the state came to the university and said we want?
No, the Transformation Institute was an idea of Mr. Gilchrist, who was at that time the Chancellor, and a man who was for many, many years the Chief of the Bureau of Public Works, McDonald.
They felt that there should be more cooperation between the major universities in the states and the state power departments to solve the problem of the climate system.
And so they decided that Texas was a good place to try this out and see if they could start it here.
And Ms. Skelter's got that legislation passed by the legislature, and it was pretty adept at being in the legislature back in the early 50s.
It was a deal that we did, and it kind of came about in 1954-55.
McDonnell retired from the Bureau of Public Roads and came down here and was on our staff for a number of years.
And they started the corporate forum.
And how did you get into the position of Vice Director of TEAS?
Well, I started out with TTI.
It came to me when somebody younger looked after the business side of this operation and somebody who was familiar with the university.
system in the University of the People.
They made me an executive officer in the Transformation Institute.
I was a professor of civil engineering there.
So I was at the same time an administrator for the Transformation Institute on half-time wages.
And we started, essentially, with nothing.

We built that program, and actually we had a real feud with the Engineering and Sperm Station, because the Highway Department was doing a little bit of work through the Engineering and Sperm Station, and they moved it over to the Transportation Institute.
Art Mello, who was the advice director of the station, Dean was always the director, and he was very unhappy about that.
That's why he left?
That was one of the reasons he left.
The real reason he left, I guess, was the fact that he had gone to Calhoun, and he said, I know, I know.
He was the kind of one who had an aggressive program.
What program?
Aggressive program that he was willing to carry on.
And director Rose, who came right before you?
No, after me.
Right, in terms of right before you became director?
No, after me.
Oh, okay.
The metal left.
Dr. Kalzin came to me and wanted me to
take on the job of, again, Vice Director of the Experiment Station along with me and the Executive Officer of TTI.
I didn't really want to do it, but I finally agreed to it.
And I became then the Vice Director of the Experiment Station and the Executive Officer of TTI at the same time.

John was, of course, a very aggressive individual, and they were working on the plans for the nuclear science center, trying to get it developed, and closing the loop and wind tunnel, and affecting a useful piece of equipment.
Then they changed the format of the general administration here,
I went back to the system organization, which they had dropped.
I got in the team.
I was the vice president for engineering.
I forgot what the title was.
And they wanted me to be dean of engineering, so I became dean of engineering.
And I was always very involved with the team.
The director of the Experiment Station.
Was he here at the University before that?
No, he was not.
He was only here about a year back.
Well, he wasn't here very long.
I thought it was longer than that because Mr. Rutter came and
in the spring of 58.
He became dean in December of 57.
And Carter became the vice president.
Sometime later, and I don't remember exactly when it was, they made him president of the university, kept the system in resignation, but they moved the experiment stations and the extension services
for administrative purposes of the university.
And when they did that, Dr. Calhoun essentially got out of the job.
And he went to the Bureau of the Interior with our science advisor for three or four years, and then he came back and worked as a vice chancellor for our parents.
Did Rose leave because of greater pastors or because of the difference in...
He was upset about the change in military.
Was it a change in the direction he saw T's going?
I think so, yes.
He just felt that they were trying not to continue the same policies that had been followed
So when he left, then Mr. Rudner wanted me to again become Director of Experiment Center, which I did.
From that time on then, I was responsible for all of the engineering activities until 1978.
That's what a lot of the sources, most of them said you were
continuously director, but a few things, including a Houston Post article I saw, said that Dr. Cahan was director.
I was the research manager.
I saw an article that said he was named.
I had much time with the research manager.
He was with the research manager.
Much rather didn't like the way he ran it, so he made me director of it, too.
All for a while.
Did they...
essentially become one administrative organization?
The Research Foundation really is a separate corp for me.
For a while, he didn't really want fire to go on, so what he did was to make him
the vice-director or something of the experimental section in the meeting, something that kind of eased out.
He decided that he wanted to talk about it, so he might be working on it.
It's not a very similar position.
How did President Rutter change the way he changes policies or goals?
Mr. Rutter wasn't, wasn't one to tell you how to do things.
What he did was give you a job and expect you to get on with it.
As far as the policies were concerned, he was the only guy that could obey the rules and get into anybody's hair too much while I ran suit and set.
So the policies that we had, pretty much the policies that we developed inside of our engineering community, between myself and the department.
Did you find that Sputnik and all the signs of the education bill after launching changed the tease out of it all, or defunded it?
I would say yes, it did both.
Probably had more effect on funding than it did on what we were trying to do.
After Sputnik, the federal funding for science and engineering research and development increased, so there were a great many more sources of funds, and the fellows who had ideas
had much more opportunity to get them exported than they had before them.
Back in the early years, 1940s and 1950s,
Essentially, there was very little federal funding available to normal universities.
There were special activities like the University of California operations, places like that, MIT, Lincoln Laboratories.
As far as general funding available, the federal government doesn't exist.

So the early programs were rather involved entirely on what funds you could get from the state of Texas and the work that we did for the private industries of the state and the highway department, of course, and the TTI program.
That was a very substantial program for us.
The wind tunnel you mentioned earlier, is that the same wind tunnel they're using now?
The wind tunnel was originally built with a concrete section that was open to both ends.
And the tunnel at that time had very, very little value.
It had very little control.
We got about the same amount of money out of the University Community Welfare Fund.
and also put it in the balance system at that time.
So it's been improved over the years, it seems?
It's been improved some since the balance system was installed back in the 50s.
It was originally for agriculture airplanes.
Well, no, it was a general low speed wind tunnel.
They used it a lot for their aggregate plane test, but we used it for other things.
The biggest problem we had at that time was with insertion and expulsion.
But they were more interested in the problems involved in spraying chemicals
Dispersion solids and that sort of thing.
It did that work with full-scale airplanes and feet.
One of the other research areas that was big in the 50s but kind of dropped off was the architectural research in ventilation.
That work was started under Dr. Mello.
And it sensed that he was the brainchild of Bill Cordell, who was an architect at that time.
And they worked on some of the same things that Gieske had worked on.
Natural elevation, lighting, they worked on lighting, they worked on beam.
air conditioning was just beginning to come in in those days.
And then that program later shifted over and they did a lot of work for the military in the general area of protection of buildings from radiation problems in the latter few years.
in this area, and most of that work was classified.
That's the problem.
I had to find out a lot of what was going on in the 60s because so much of the output is classified.
But the work of Caudill and his people there was actually poor.
There's a lot of reinventing the wheel going on in this country today.
We're going to be going back to St. Petersburg.
And he went in a private...
Yes, he and two other fellows, a member of the staff over there, one of our graduate students, started an architectural firm here in Bryan, William Ralph and Scott, and they became...
from a substantial firm in a fairly short period of time, about five, six, eight years.
And then they moved their business to Houston, and they're still active in Houston now.
And Rowlett are both gone.
Wally Scott is still there, as far as I know.
That sort of lost track of the people who did the, you know, the search work for them.
There's an awful lot of people to keep track of.
Besides President Rutter, is anyone else, and he was here for so long during that great spur of development, is anyone else in terms of President or Chancellor had a great impact on the re-operation?
His impact being who left you alone to do it.
Well, Mr. Rutter, of course, always said,
was very supportive of anything that we wanted to do in the developmental area.
And Williams also was supportive in that respect.
He was never interested in the work that we were doing in the engineering department.
It was his field of liberal arts.
I didn't know very much about it, but the work developed quite well in the period when William was Chancellor.
Probably one of the reasons for that is at that time Calhoun was, or they called him, they changed the titles all the time, but he was
You see, Mr. Rutter and Dr. Williams were both Chancellor and President of the California Board of Supervisors.
I think they called the Calhoun Dean of the Faculty.
Maybe he was the Vice President later.
Anyway, he had the same job as Eaton and Phillips put together.
And were there any big, your other interview you said that the 70s was a time of organizing all that had been done in the 60s and just developing that further.
Were there any big new projects that you were thinking about in the 70s?
Well, in the 70s, of course, we started the space program.
I guess in the 70s, we primarily developed our remote sensing program in the 70s.
Was there any of the space program in the 60s?
There probably was some.
I think probably the big development in the space program was late 60s, early 70s.
We started our solid-state electronics program.
I guess, again, we began that in the 60s with the major development in that arena within the 70s.
And the transportation is due, of course.
We began our highway safety program.
And again, that was started back in the early to middle 60s, I guess.
it probably made its greatest advances in the 70s.
Since then, what happened in the 70s, a lot of what we had started earlier, more or less, came with maturity.
Did you have, most of the 60s were contracted?
Most of everything was contracted.
So were the findings
Besides those things that were classified for defense reasons, there wasn't much that wasn't classified?
There wasn't much that was classified.
The only thing that I can remember is doing the classified arena after the work that we were doing on radiation was in geophysics.
and quite a lot of classified work in geophysics in terms of the detection of nuclear attacks.
We did only a very, very small amount of classified work.
The biggest thing was the steady growth of the program.
When I started, I guess it was in the late 50s.
It was probably 250.
When I left, I guess it was quite early.
I don't remember the exact date.
Was most of the 60s government contract or private industry contract?
Most of the 60s government contract.
Did that change any in the 70s?
Generally speaking, we did more work in private industry in the 70s than we had in the 60s.
And then we began to also emphasize our relations with industry, both from the standpoint of the research
teaching program so that we could make our program more sensitive to the real world.
Was there a particular time period that this was an administrative decision to be delayed, or was this for them?
Well, I think we probably decided in roughly 1970 that this was the direction in which we ought to go.
And we also, of course, decided that engineering would probably
move in the same way the law of medicine had, we would have essentially separate schools.
That would be a mistake because I don't think it would happen.
At least as far as our policies are concerned, they would be pointed in that direction.
Based on that point.
When did interdisciplinary research
I don't remember.
But must have come here in 58 or 59.
So I would guess we started the Interdisciplinary Research Program in the 1960s.
And of course, it always had a rocky path.
It still does to a large extent.
Universities remain to this day.
Apartments are too much for the shops, they don't talk to each other.
And it's very difficult to cross those barriers.
I've never quite understood why.
Even in engineering it's sometimes difficult between mechanical, electrical, electrical, and industrial or civil mechanics.
Is there a particular period in the history of tea since you've been here that you consider to be the low period?
Well, the lowest period, as far as I'm concerned, is when I first started.
We didn't have much program, and we didn't have very many people in there who were interested in research.
Are there
Any projects that you remember, any pet projects that you think should have been pursued in one of those?
There were many over the years you would love to do.
Well, there were lots of things that we would like to have done, but we couldn't find the support to do them.
I don't know, several deaths.
I've got the idea for instance.

One of the solutions to the water problem here in Texas might be building the major nuclear reactors on the coast and use the salt water for cooling and evaporate the salt water and evaporate the water.
To me, that's a fascinating scheme.
I'm looking forward to it.
Is that the 60s?
Yes, we were on that end of the 60s.
We were on that end of the 60s.
But here again, this was all we did, which was preliminary studies on this.
It became obvious that we were going to go against federal government.
He operates on the charter that's in the legislation that created it.
And as far as I know, that's the only
The guidelines that it has are very general.
Now, the key is the subject of all the rules and regulations of the university system.

Essentially, its job is to do research, which is important for the state of Texas, and which will support the Texas economy and support the engineering activity and other activities here at the university.
What do you think the role of TEAS is in terms of education?

Well, the role of TEAS in education is to provide the faculty with opportunities to engage in research in which they're interested or to engage in these projects of interdisciplinary nature in which they may not be so interested.
We use that to support graduate students and build up the faculty confidence and build up the store of the world of information on how we do things.
And how do you feel teaching is responsible to disseminate the information?
Well, certainly it has a responsibility to disseminate.
the information and the question always is, how is this to be done?
That's the most difficult job of all.
You've got to get the information that you've developed out.
You can do this through saying that your people get to technical meetings where their colleagues will know what they're doing here and publishing articles and research reports
books, all sorts of things.
I don't think that there were any years that I hadn't gone and built a book program, but we did a very good job and felt that was one of our weak links.
It's been hard for me trying to pull the history together with a few publications, but I noticed that
Lewis Horne, who apparently was... Lewis Horne came to work for a man who was a vice director before me.
No.
When he switched to TTI, he said everything kind of dropped off and everything.
Get another man like him.
The decision was made at that time.
The department had felt that it was better for their people to publish in the open literature than it was for us to continue this series in which we published many of ourselves in our publications.
I'm not so sure, but that was a wise decision.
When you do that, the material becomes very scattered.
Nobody takes responsibility for seeing that you have copies of the veil, that sort of thing.
And I just doubt that that is as effective as the old bulletin circuitry.
But then again, I don't know.
It does not like me.
In the 1972 bulletin, there was another effort with the change in attitude in the 70s to take a new responsibility.
It was just a general news bulletin you sent out to industry and researchers.
That was probably more in the order of an advertising piece to try to get more support from industry.
really dissimilar type of thing.
Oh, it's not technical, of course, in any sense, but it was kind of, we have some of this, and if you want it, we'll get it.
When I, I mean, Dr. Porter, who took my place, this is one of the things that I told you that you should work on.
I think you've done a pretty good job.
I think you did a much better job now.
We were doing a much better job.
Did the Vietnam War have much of an effect on the direction some of your research was going?
Really not.
We never did get involved in classified work in 1944.
Some of our people did.
Some of our people worked in classified programs.
They did this route just like Sam did.
As far as the station is concerned, I don't remember anything.
What about the strategic?
Center for Strategic Technology?
That came later.
That was an idea that Dr. Thomas and I had, and I think that idea probably surfaced
sometime along in the early or middle 70s.
There were, of course, a large number of these think tanks around the country which had influenced the policy of like the minor corporations, grand corporations, like that.
And these groups were either on the east coast or on the west coast.
And we felt, by and large, that many of their studies were highly biased by their geographic location.
And that there was room for a group which was really, had people in it who thought somewhat differently.
And this was a good place for our panel.
So we started out, got this approved by the board, and it was up and coming.
been operating for about five or six years, and we are now beginning to have pretty substantial growth.
The food protein program, is that out of the cotton seed?
That's out of the old cotton seed products library.
The Cotton Committee of Texas back somewhere in, oh, I guess in the late 30s,
to convince the state of Texas that they ought to put in a parachute program in cotton.
So they essentially divided that program into four units.
The unit concerned with the use of cotton and the production of cotton crops along with the Texas Tech.
Work on privacy was done here.
The work on clothing and so on was done at what was then the Texas State College for Women in Denton.
And the University of Texas had a very small program in the economic school.
And programs don't very much exist that way.
Spinning work and so on is still all done at Tech.
The cottonseed work is done here.
And the work on the use of cotton primarily in women's clothing is done up at, what do we call it now?
TSCW?
TW.
TW.
That's where I got my master's.
And they produce some real beautiful things.
But we changed the program.
We changed the program and made it much broader than that.
They now work with all kinds of .
Essentially, the thrust of that program today is to develop local sources of .
That was developed in the 60s, that expanded.
Right.
It was really gone under way when we brought Carl into it.
I think he came probably somewhere in the late 60s.
The fan test.
It's been here forever.
Fan testing was a part of the Easton program.
I talked about that first.
And since he was interested in ventilation and movement of air, it was pretty much natural for them to develop interest in performance of fans.
And so we got some people over in the engineering department to work on this.
And out of the work that they did, developed really the Fan Manufacturers Association in this country.
And this laboratory which does the official fan tests and provides them with the information that they use in their advertisements.
So where it started out to be a research laboratory, and in its early years,
Did a lot of fun about researching fans.
It is now a, I guess you would call it a regulatory factory.
And produces, tests the fans and makes sure that the manufacturer's claims are.
It's like a good housekeeping team.
Yeah.
Same thing for the fans.
Except we do it all.
The fan manufacturers don't even bother to do their own tests now.
They send their fans in here and we make them make up the tables for them.
It's a cheaper reading for each one of them.
They have very fine stuff to sell.
It has expanded some to consider fan noises and other elements of the system.
But essentially it's a measurement laboratory.
Although they know a lot about moving air.
The cyclotron has always been interesting.
A cyclotron was really sort of a funny, funny thing.
Mr. Rutter called me up one day after a hot July day and said, I want you to go to Houston with me and talk to the Browns Foundation about cyclotrons.
I knew barely what a cyclotron was.
But we got in the car and went down and talked to the Welch Foundation, the Welch Foundation people.
And they decided they would provide a million dollars for construction of the cyclotron.
And they wanted A&M to take on the responsibility of getting the rest of the money and getting it built and getting it in operation.
So when we got back, we heard from the other fellows who were in the field who were studying in the US.
And they were smiling where I could get any attention.
And we were looking at our salary, which at that time was going to cost, I think, about $300,000.
All we had was better knowledge from the Welsh Foundation.
And Mr. Rutter was pretty sure that he'd get the board to match that, but he didn't think he'd get any more than that, so that's too many numbers.
And my people said, well, the best people.
And cyclotrons of the size that we were planning to build are located at Lawrence Radiation Lab in Berkley.
So we got the man who built their 88-inch cyclotron.
to come here and advise us how we should proceed and give us some ideas of what we would do with the costs and operational expenses and that sort of thing.
And we did a report from Mr.
Rudder and the board and they decided they wanted to go on with it if we could raise the money.
The Welch Foundation people had done some preliminary work with the
At that time Al Ludeke was the general manager of the Atomic Energy Commission and one of our graduates of course.
So we went to Pierce, who was their research manager, and he encouraged us to go on.
And he essentially was responsible, I expect, along with Ludeke.
for getting the additional money put in the federal budget for us to build this type of thing.
Now, after all of the legwork of the...
